pull.title: [API BREAK] Remove _t in types due to being POSIX-reserved
pull.body:
Fixes #198.

Builds on top of #293.

Mechanical application of

`
for A in include/*.h src/*.h src/*.c src/modules/*/*.h; do sed -e 's/secp256k1_\([a-z_]*\)_t\([^a-zA-Z]\)/secp256k1_\1\2/g' <$A >/tmp/bla; mv /tmp/bla $A; sed -e 's/callback_t/secp256k1_callback/g' <$A >/tmp/bla; mv /tmp/bla $A; done
`

milestone.title: stable release (1.0.0-rc.1)
milestone.description:
Motivation: libsecp is already widely used today, but often in a terribly outdated version. It's likely that a release process would help with that. Moreover, it simplifies using libsecp which may prevent developers from using less well tested alternatives. Lastly, without releases it's difficult to update the library in an organized fashion and communicate these updates.

Release Goals:

- Stabilize API and documentation for functionality that exist today.
- Fix a few known bugs.
- Make ECDH non-experimental.

This milestone can be discussed in issue https://github.com/bitcoin-core/secp256k1/issues/286.

events.body:
> for A in include/_.h src/_.h src/_.c src/modules/_/*.h; do sed -e  <$A >/tmp/bla; mv /tmp/bla $A; sed -e  <$A >/tmp/bla; mv /tmp/bla $A; done

Seems a bit fancy,  any reason to not just use `-i` on sed?

```
sed -i 's/secp256k1_\([a-z_]*\)_t\([^a-zA-Z]\)/secp256k1_\1_type\2/g' `find include/ src/ | grep "\.\(c\|h\)$"`
```
@dcousens I'll use that if I need to redo it :)
ACK without reading the code ("only-tested ACK?"); but I ran the tests binary and benchmarks on 512 different ./configure setups with no problems.
As suggested by @rustyrussell: just drop the _t instead of replacing by _type.
